---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const openingExample = `Ask first:
Why does CSS feel harder than it should?

Usually not because CSS is difficult.
Usually because ownership is unclear.`;

const fifteenMinuteFlow = `15 minute teaching flow
→ The real problem
→ The non-negotiables
→ Decision rules
→ Common anti-patterns
→ Adoption without rewrites
→ What good looks like`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="Teaching Deck"
    description="Explain Layered Semantic CSS to a team in 15 minutes."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Teaching deck</p>
        <h1>Explain LSCSS in 15 minutes</h1>
        <p class="intro">
            Good methodology fails when it takes an hour to explain and nobody
            remembers it on Tuesday. This page is the short version for teams,
            workshops, onboarding, and architecture buy-in.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Teaching deck sections">
        <a href="#opening">Start first</a>
        <a href="#problem">The real problem</a>
        <a href="#principles">Non-negotiables</a>
        <a href="#patterns">Bad patterns</a>
        <a href="#adoption">Safe adoption</a>
        <a href="#close">Close strong</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="opening" class="content-block">
        <h2>Open with the real question</h2>
        <CodeExample code={openingExample} language="text" />
        <p>
            Start with delivery pain, not naming theory. People adopt systems
            when they recognise the problem first.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="problem" class="content-block">
        <h2>The real problem</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Overrides feel unpredictable</li>
            <li>Developers disagree where CSS should live</li>
            <li>Utilities quietly become architecture</li>
            <li>Legacy CSS spreads like folklore</li>
            <li>Everyone fears one shared stylesheet</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            This is rarely a CSS syntax problem. It is usually an ownership problem.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="principles" class="content-block">
        <h2>The non-negotiables</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Ownership before selectors</li>
            <li>Layers before specificity</li>
            <li>Shallow selectors over deep nesting</li>
            <li>Utilities are exceptions</li>
            <li>Hacks are temporary</li>
            <li>Tokens before random values</li>
            <li>Calm CSS beats clever CSS</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="patterns" class="content-block">
        <h2>Show the common crimes</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Deep selectors hiding ownership problems</li>
            <li>Important declarations replacing architecture</li>
            <li>Modifier names hiding temporary state</li>
            <li>Magic numbers becoming design decisions</li>
            <li>Temporary hacks surviving multiple Christmases</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            People learn fast when they recognise their own code in the evidence.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="adoption" class="content-block">
        <h2>Adoption without rewrites</h2>
        <CodeExample code={fifteenMinuteFlow} language="text" />
        <p>
            Start with layers. Protect new work first. Improve active
            components. Do not declare CSS bankruptcy for dramatic effect.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="close" class="content-block">
        <h2>Close with this</h2>
        <p>
            Good CSS is not impressive because it is clever. It is impressive
            because nobody is afraid to change it.
        </p>

        <p>
            The goal is not perfect code. The goal is safer delivery.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>Next useful pages</h2>
        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/principles/">Principles</a></h3>
                <p>Use the short version when teaching, and the full version when challenged.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/examples/">Examples</a></h3>
                <p>Support the teaching deck with practical before and after proof.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/adoption/">Adoption</a></h3>
                <p>Turn team agreement into actual implementation without chaos.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
